04 Jul 2009 03:40






The short answer is, if 743 doesn't get enough people to eat, it gets… cranky. The medium-length answer is, the Foundation had originally tried to contain 743 without providing any people to eat— plenty of plants and live animals. 743 breached containment and chowed down on whomever was available. After some trial and error, researchers determined that if 743 is given a live person to eat every two to three days, it won't try to breach containment. The long answer is an incident log that I need to write up at some point detailing this process.

As for the numbers and timing of D-class fed to 743: the D-class that are on 743's menu were already slated for termination. Their termination date has just been pushed back a couple of weeks, at most. I reckon I could make that clearer in the article, though.

Thanks everyone for the feedback!







